00:00:43.458 --> 00:00:45.959
because every time they built a levee somewhere

00:00:45.959 --> 00:00:48.792
that area wouldn’t flood but a town just a few miles down

00:00:48.792 --> 00:00:50.750
would be destroyed

00:00:50.750 --> 00:00:54.375
they didn’t understand how the river really worked

00:00:54.375 --> 00:00:57.583
Corporal Eugene Reybold, this guy had a genius idea

00:00:57.583 --> 00:01:00.208
he was like “Why don’t we model it?"

00:01:00.208 --> 00:01:02.291
And what this meant was literally

00:01:02.291 --> 00:01:05.792
why don’t we build a gigantic model of it?

00:01:08.792 --> 00:01:11.041
So the notion was, let’s make a scale model

00:01:11.041 --> 00:01:13.542
a tiny version of the entire Mississippi river basin

00:01:13.542 --> 00:01:15.375
the scale of this model is amazing

00:01:15.375 --> 00:01:19.458
it meant building a model of 40% of the entire US

00:01:19.458 --> 00:01:21.375
eight miles of tiny streams

00:01:21.375 --> 00:01:26.166
It’s so big you can’t see it except from a plane or helicopter

00:01:26.166 --> 00:01:28.166
because it’s spread out over 200 acres

00:01:28.166 --> 00:01:29.458
the whole thing was a hydraulic model

00:01:29.458 --> 00:01:34.959
so they could just pull a lever and run through an entire flood

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:36.875
and it let them put up little levees

00:01:36.875 --> 00:01:38.667
and figure out “OK, if we put up a levee here, 

00:01:38.667 --> 00:01:41.458
 what happens down the river?"

